### Maximum Provider Version Constraint with Tilde Operator

Source: https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/providers/requirements

Use the `~>` operator to specify a maximum provider version, allowing only patch releases within a specific minor release. This is recommended for root modules to avoid accidental upgrades to incompatible versions.

```terraform
terraform {
  required_providers {
    mycloud = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "~> 1.0.4"
    }
  }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Minimum Provider Version Constraint

Source: https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/providers/requirements

Declare the minimum provider version a module is known to work with using the `>=` version constraint syntax. This ensures compatibility with at least the specified version.

```terraform
terraform {
  required_providers {
    mycloud = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = ">= 1.0"
    }
  }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Define Terraform Version Constraint (Pessimistic Constraint)

Source: https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/tutorials/configuration-language/versions

Use '~>' to specify a range of acceptable versions. This example allows any Terraform v1.7.x version but not v1.8.0 or later. This is recommended for allowing non-disruptive patch updates.

```hcl
terraform {
  required_version = "~> 1.7.5"
}

```

### language/providers/requirements.md > Best Practices for Provider Versions

Source: https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/providers/requirements

For modules intended for reuse, declare the minimum provider version using `>=`. For root modules (where `terraform apply` is run), specify both minimum and maximum versions using `~>` to prevent accidental upgrades to incompatible versions. Avoid using maximum version constraints for reusable modules to allow users to manage their own versioning.

--------------------------------

### Terraform Home > Version constraints > Best practices > Terraform core and provider versions

Source: https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/expressions/version-constraints

Reusable modules should constrain only their minimum allowed versions of Terraform and providers (e.g., `>= 0.12.0`) to prevent incompatibilities while allowing user flexibility. Root modules should use a `~>` constraint to define both lower and upper bounds for provider versions.

